  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions involves several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Initial anti-money laundering efforts emerged in the 1920s during Prohibition era in the United States\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970):\n- First comprehensive U.S. legislation addressing financial record-keeping\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Aimed at tracking potential criminal financial activities\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- Established money laundering as a criminal offense\n- Encouraged international cooperation in combating financial crimes\n\n4. Key Milestones:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for preventing money laundering\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for national legal frameworks\n\n5. Post-9/11 Enhancements:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded money laundering prohibitions\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n\n6. Modern Regulatory Framework:\n- Comprehensive international and national regulations\n- Strict compliance requirements for financial institutions\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\nThese developments reflect an evolving legal approach to combating financial crimes.",
